arch:property.oc:show_val: A medium-size midden unit of almost entirely burnt bones. All of the bones in this unit were burnt or carbonized but there is no calcination or any evidence for burning at high temperatures. There is no pattern to which bones are burnt or carbonized, but carbonized bones are completely carbonized and burnt bones are completely burnt. The burning makes other modifications difficult to see, but on the whole the bones are in good condition. There is a small amount of carnivore gnawing, with a number of long bones with articular ends gnawed off by dogs, but little digestion (in the dry-sieved anyway). Fragment size is highly variable ranging from small highly processed fragments to complete equid metapodials. Probably about 15% of the assemblage is greater than 5 cm, and there are a number greater than 10, but the average size is 2 or 3 cm. Edges are sharp and there is no polishing or trampling. Sheep and goat are the most common species and their bones tend to be highly processed. All elements are represented including large numbers of ribs and vertebrae in the scrap as well as limb, axial skeleton and horn cores. Teeth and toes are, as usual, common but do not dominate. In fact, the sheep/goat carcasses are very complete. All ages are present including a lot of infantile and early juvenile bones. Other species include large and small equid, cattle, pig and badger. Each of these species is represented by a few limb/axial bones and some feet. There are a small number of bird and fish bones and one bone point, and a fragment of burnt human skull. Overall the material looks like a rich, mixed midden deposit. The number of large, whole or almost whole bones mixed in with the usual highly processed fragments is puzzling. This may be due to protection from postdepositional destruction due to the shallow pit the material was in, or related to the burning event. However, the bones do not seem to have been directly related to the lime-burning-like event. They are not burnt enough to have been in contact with a hot fire for very long. The entire processing sequence of the sheep and goat, from butchering to bone point all seem to be present here. Overall the assemblage looks very domestic, rather than specialized, or special event-like, despite the large fragments and species list. X1 is a small complete point. A second bone point was found in the dry sieve. Shell, pottery, microfauna, fish and bird were all pulled for further analysis. Sample 2 >4mm flotation 100% sorted, recorded as diagnostics and flot frags only. It resembles the rest of the unit. While fragment size is on the whole smaller, it is still quite large, and most of the smaller pieces are the result of fragmentation in the flotation machine. It is remarkably free of the usual little rolled bits of background noise. There are few, but some digested bones here. All are still burnt in the same ways. It is heavily sheep-size, and sheep/goat predominate among the many diagnostics, although equid and dog also occur, as well as more fish and bird and one microfaunal long bone shaft. Among the sheep-size animals, body part distribution is generally remarkably even, with a lot of vertebrae and ribs, including some rib heads. However, feet are notably under-represented, especially phalanges. Cranial material is also on the low side. Horn core in particular is totally absent except for one little fragment, which is also one of only two calcined specimens in the sample.
Nerissa Russell(bone tools and flot), Sheelagh Frame

arch:string.div: The unique identifier for each contextual unit, matching those used in the central Çatalhöyük excavation database and in publications. The excavation uses single-context recording.
